00:00:07.516 --> 00:00:19.606 A:middle
[ Music ]

00:00:20.106 --> 00:00:20.656 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Hi everyone.

00:00:20.866 --> 00:00:22.246 A:middle
I'm Conor Hughes, an engineer

00:00:22.246 --> 00:00:23.746 A:middle
on the Accessibility
Team here at Apple.

00:00:24.126 --> 00:00:26.086 A:middle
And welcome to What's
New in Accessibility.

00:00:26.786 --> 00:00:29.166 A:middle
Today we're going to learn about
some cool new assistive features

00:00:29.166 --> 00:00:31.746 A:middle
in our operating systems and
learn about what you need

00:00:31.746 --> 00:00:34.776 A:middle
to know to make sure your
apps are usable by everyone.

00:00:35.266 --> 00:00:36.166 A:middle
So let's get started.

00:00:37.196 --> 00:00:39.116 A:middle
So accessibility is a big word

00:00:39.116 --> 00:00:40.316 A:middle
and many are not
familiar with it.

00:00:40.646 --> 00:00:41.286 A:middle
What does it mean?

00:00:41.546 --> 00:00:44.636 A:middle
To us, accessibility means
making a system usable

00:00:44.636 --> 00:00:47.216 A:middle
for everyone, with all
of their unique needs.

00:00:48.086 --> 00:00:50.316 A:middle
This means both designing
in accommodations for people

00:00:50.316 --> 00:00:52.166 A:middle
with different needs
and being careful

00:00:52.166 --> 00:00:54.056 A:middle
about your basic
design to avoid issues.

00:00:54.806 --> 00:00:57.886 A:middle
This being WWDC, we're going
to focus on accessibility

00:00:57.886 --> 00:00:59.856 A:middle
on Apple platforms
where we're concerned

00:00:59.856 --> 00:01:02.436 A:middle
with four major classes
of ability: Motor,


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:00:59.856 --> 00:01:02.436 A:middle
with four major classes
of ability: Motor,

00:01:02.706 --> 00:01:04.775 A:middle
vision, hearing and learning.

00:01:06.586 --> 00:01:08.666 A:middle
Motor encompasses
things like Parkinson's

00:01:08.666 --> 00:01:11.446 A:middle
and Multiple Sclerosis and
affects things like the ability

00:01:11.446 --> 00:01:14.646 A:middle
to push with force on the screen
or accurately tap targets.

00:01:16.076 --> 00:01:18.316 A:middle
Vision accommodations
encompass both blindness

00:01:18.316 --> 00:01:19.596 A:middle
and partial vision loss.

00:01:21.416 --> 00:01:23.626 A:middle
Hearing covers hearing
loss of various gradations.

00:01:24.946 --> 00:01:27.686 A:middle
And learning, which includes
things like dyslexia and autism.

00:01:28.106 --> 00:01:31.266 A:middle
Our operating systems can do a
lot to provide accommodations

00:01:31.266 --> 00:01:32.356 A:middle
in all of these areas.

00:01:32.776 --> 00:01:35.466 A:middle
But apps are a core part of
our platform experiences.

00:01:35.776 --> 00:01:38.236 A:middle
So for our platforms to be
truly accessible environments,

00:01:38.496 --> 00:01:41.216 A:middle
we need you to make sure your
apps are accessible as well,

00:01:41.536 --> 00:01:43.626 A:middle
which is why we're so happy
that you're here to learn

00:01:43.626 --> 00:01:44.866 A:middle
about how to do just that.

00:01:45.336 --> 00:01:47.016 A:middle
So let's go over what we're
going to talk about today.

00:01:47.556 --> 00:01:49.926 A:middle
First we'll go over some of
the new assistive features

00:01:49.926 --> 00:01:52.916 A:middle
in Mac OS, iOS, watchOS and tvOS

00:01:52.916 --> 00:01:55.316 A:middle
so you can see some
concrete examples

00:01:55.316 --> 00:01:57.566 A:middle
of how software can
provide accommodations

00:01:57.566 --> 00:01:58.666 A:middle
for people with different needs.

00:01:59.276 --> 00:02:01.906 A:middle
Then we'll take an iOS app
as our example and audit it


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:01:59.276 --> 00:02:01.906 A:middle
Then we'll take an iOS app
as our example and audit it

00:02:01.906 --> 00:02:03.116 A:middle
for accessibility issues.

00:02:04.476 --> 00:02:06.566 A:middle
Then dig into the
APIs that you can use

00:02:06.566 --> 00:02:08.336 A:middle
to make sure your
apps are accessible.

00:02:09.735 --> 00:02:11.376 A:middle
And finally, we'll
use those APIs

00:02:11.376 --> 00:02:13.516 A:middle
to fix the issues we
identified in our audit,

00:02:13.746 --> 00:02:16.626 A:middle
including using some new API
we think you're going to love.

00:02:17.076 --> 00:02:19.046 A:middle
So what new assistive features
do we have to show this year?

00:02:19.596 --> 00:02:22.386 A:middle
Well, there are quite a few, so
let's go through and take a look

00:02:22.386 --> 00:02:24.736 A:middle
at what's new in
each major area.

00:02:26.316 --> 00:02:27.436 A:middle
First off, motor.

00:02:28.086 --> 00:02:32.476 A:middle
So some people may only be able
to interact with their devise

00:02:32.476 --> 00:02:34.186 A:middle
through pressing a
single physical button,

00:02:34.186 --> 00:02:36.896 A:middle
for instance a switch on
a wheelchair headrest.

00:02:37.566 --> 00:02:40.096 A:middle
They can interact with the
rich touch interface of iOS,

00:02:40.096 --> 00:02:42.946 A:middle
for instance, through Switch
Control, which presents a cursor

00:02:42.946 --> 00:02:45.156 A:middle
which moves through the
interface elements on screen.

00:02:46.026 --> 00:02:47.966 A:middle
When someone wants to
interact with the element

00:02:47.966 --> 00:02:49.926 A:middle
under the cursor, they
press their switch.

00:02:50.556 --> 00:02:53.326 A:middle
Switch Control lets people with
motor disabilities do everything

00:02:53.326 --> 00:02:55.596 A:middle
from simple taps to
complex gestures.

00:02:56.696 --> 00:02:59.646 A:middle
iOS and OS X have had Switch
Control for several years.

00:02:59.646 --> 00:03:00.176 A:middle
So what's new?


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:02:59.646 --> 00:03:00.176 A:middle
So what's new?

00:03:01.806 --> 00:03:02.946 A:middle
Well, we're excited to announce

00:03:02.946 --> 00:03:05.066 A:middle
that we're bringing
Switch Control to tvOS.

00:03:05.716 --> 00:03:07.646 A:middle
Now, people who use
Switch Control can use it

00:03:07.646 --> 00:03:09.916 A:middle
to directly interact
with the tvOS interface.

00:03:10.586 --> 00:03:12.886 A:middle
The familiar Switch interface
is available with that cursor

00:03:12.886 --> 00:03:14.216 A:middle
that highlights elements
onscreen.

00:03:15.036 --> 00:03:17.256 A:middle
Or an alternative
interface is available

00:03:17.256 --> 00:03:18.306 A:middle
with an onscreen remote.

00:03:19.066 --> 00:03:20.786 A:middle
And what's more,
people can do this

00:03:20.786 --> 00:03:22.306 A:middle
without repairing their switch.

00:03:23.166 --> 00:03:26.166 A:middle
Someone using Switch
Control on their iOS device

00:03:26.166 --> 00:03:28.656 A:middle
or their Mac can immediately
start controlling their TV

00:03:28.926 --> 00:03:31.496 A:middle
totally autonomously
without any external help.

00:03:32.056 --> 00:03:33.456 A:middle
We think this is a
huge improvement.

00:03:33.456 --> 00:03:36.966 A:middle
And we can't wait for
people to try it out.

00:03:37.226 --> 00:03:38.426 A:middle
Next up, Dwell Control.

00:03:39.166 --> 00:03:40.886 A:middle
There are a number of
assistive technologies

00:03:40.886 --> 00:03:43.226 A:middle
that track someone's focus when
they're using their computer.

00:03:43.586 --> 00:03:45.996 A:middle
So they may take the form
of tracking a reflective dot

00:03:45.996 --> 00:03:48.696 A:middle
on a headband, or actually
tracking eye movements.

00:03:49.516 --> 00:03:51.816 A:middle
Dwell Control is a
new feature in Mac OS,

00:03:51.816 --> 00:03:53.586 A:middle
which integrates
support for these devices

00:03:53.836 --> 00:03:55.256 A:middle
by allowing them to
control the mouse.

00:03:55.916 --> 00:03:57.926 A:middle
When the mouse dwells
on a certain location,

00:03:58.556 --> 00:03:59.956 A:middle
Dwell Control presents
a timer [inaudible].

00:03:59.956 --> 00:04:02.826 A:middle
And when a timer expires,
it invokes an action,


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:03:59.956 --> 00:04:02.826 A:middle
And when a timer expires,
it invokes an action,

00:04:02.876 --> 00:04:03.886 A:middle
for instance a mouse click.

00:04:04.696 --> 00:04:07.266 A:middle
This allows someone to control
their Mac without having

00:04:07.266 --> 00:04:08.376 A:middle
to manipulate the mouse.

00:04:08.626 --> 00:04:11.036 A:middle
And of course, it's customizable
with custom actions,

00:04:11.266 --> 00:04:12.156 A:middle
just like Switch Control.

00:04:12.656 --> 00:04:14.176 A:middle
So next, let's look at vision.

00:04:15.296 --> 00:04:18.745 A:middle
So, for many years Mac OS and
iOS have supported features

00:04:18.745 --> 00:04:20.315 A:middle
like invert colors
and gray scale

00:04:21.046 --> 00:04:23.526 A:middle
to help people increase
the contrast of the content

00:04:23.526 --> 00:04:25.926 A:middle
on their device, deal
with light sensitivity

00:04:25.926 --> 00:04:27.186 A:middle
or work around color issues.

00:04:27.836 --> 00:04:29.636 A:middle
This year we're expanding
that support

00:04:29.636 --> 00:04:32.116 A:middle
across Mac OS, iOS and tvOS.

00:04:32.666 --> 00:04:34.706 A:middle
We've added color
adjustments to help people

00:04:34.706 --> 00:04:37.476 A:middle
with color blindness, which
can help something that appears

00:04:37.766 --> 00:04:40.966 A:middle
like this, appear
more like this.

00:04:41.766 --> 00:04:43.366 A:middle
And we've also added the ability

00:04:43.366 --> 00:04:45.366 A:middle
to tint the entire
display a certain color,

00:04:45.756 --> 00:04:48.546 A:middle
which can significantly increase
reading ability in people

00:04:48.546 --> 00:04:52.776 A:middle
who find reading black
on white text difficult.

00:04:53.536 --> 00:04:56.026 A:middle
So in watchOS, someone using
VoiceOver can have the time

00:04:56.026 --> 00:04:58.196 A:middle
spoken aloud to them
by raising their wrist

00:04:58.196 --> 00:04:59.336 A:middle
or tapping on the watch face.

00:04:59.966 --> 00:05:02.356 A:middle
But sometimes they may want
to discretely check the time


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:04:59.966 --> 00:05:02.356 A:middle
But sometimes they may want
to discretely check the time

00:05:02.356 --> 00:05:04.116 A:middle
without disturbing
those around them.

00:05:04.296 --> 00:05:06.546 A:middle
So in watchOS 3 we're
introducing Taptic Time.

00:05:07.396 --> 00:05:10.006 A:middle
Taptic Time is a VoiceOver
feature that uses a series

00:05:10.006 --> 00:05:11.956 A:middle
of distinct taps from
the Taptic engine

00:05:11.956 --> 00:05:15.096 A:middle
to help someone tell time
silently and discretely.

00:05:15.686 --> 00:05:20.276 A:middle
So iOS has a lot of
features that help people

00:05:20.276 --> 00:05:22.596 A:middle
with visual disabilities
discover and interact

00:05:22.596 --> 00:05:23.816 A:middle
with the content
on their device.

00:05:23.856 --> 00:05:25.766 A:middle
But what about their
physical environment?

00:05:26.796 --> 00:05:29.106 A:middle
In iOS X we're introducing
a feature called Magnifier.

00:05:29.786 --> 00:05:31.986 A:middle
Magnifier is available
from anywhere in iOS.

00:05:32.606 --> 00:05:34.356 A:middle
And it lets someone use
their device's camera

00:05:34.456 --> 00:05:36.496 A:middle
to magnify objects in
their physical environment.

00:05:37.206 --> 00:05:39.886 A:middle
And I'd love to show
that to you now.

00:05:44.376 --> 00:05:46.716 A:middle
Okay, so I'm going to
turn on Magnifier by going

00:05:46.716 --> 00:05:51.626 A:middle
into Settings, General,
Accessibility, Magnifier

00:05:51.626 --> 00:05:52.596 A:middle
and flipping the switch.

00:05:53.766 --> 00:05:55.346 A:middle
Now I can turn on Magnifier

00:05:55.346 --> 00:05:56.726 A:middle
by just triple clicking
the Home button.

00:05:57.366 --> 00:05:59.066 A:middle
So here we are.

00:05:59.836 --> 00:06:02.916 A:middle
So, if I want to read what's
on this bottle of medicine,


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:05:59.836 --> 00:06:02.916 A:middle
So, if I want to read what's
on this bottle of medicine,

00:06:02.916 --> 00:06:06.846 A:middle
for instance, I can
just zoom in quite far.

00:06:06.846 --> 00:06:09.146 A:middle
I have access to things
like the camera torch

00:06:09.146 --> 00:06:10.896 A:middle
for a low light environment.

00:06:11.636 --> 00:06:13.766 A:middle
I can lock focus on a
certain focal length.

00:06:14.416 --> 00:06:17.586 A:middle
And in case I have trouble
keeping the device steady,

00:06:17.976 --> 00:06:19.396 A:middle
or I'm pointing at
something far away,

00:06:19.396 --> 00:06:23.416 A:middle
I can take a freeze frame
here with the Center button.

00:06:23.416 --> 00:06:24.926 A:middle
And we captured this image

00:06:24.926 --> 00:06:27.566 A:middle
at the device's native camera
resolution, so we can zoom

00:06:27.566 --> 00:06:29.286 A:middle
out and in, move around.

00:06:30.186 --> 00:06:33.336 A:middle
And Magnifier also supports
various color filters

00:06:33.466 --> 00:06:35.166 A:middle
to help someone increase
the contrast.

00:06:35.626 --> 00:06:38.976 A:middle
So for instance, maybe
I find this grayscale,

00:06:39.396 --> 00:06:42.696 A:middle
maybe inverted grayscale,
increase the contrast a bit.

00:06:42.906 --> 00:06:44.586 A:middle
So that's pretty
easy for me to read.

00:06:45.486 --> 00:06:48.186 A:middle
Okay, so that's an example
of Magnifier on iOS X.

00:06:49.046 --> 00:06:51.596 A:middle
Okay, so what's new in hearing?

00:06:51.886 --> 00:06:54.696 A:middle
iOS has supported hardware
TTY devices for some time.

00:06:55.396 --> 00:06:57.676 A:middle
TTY technology allows
someone with hearing loss

00:06:57.676 --> 00:07:00.956 A:middle
to hold text conversations
over standard telephone calls.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:06:57.676 --> 00:07:00.956 A:middle
to hold text conversations
over standard telephone calls.

00:07:01.496 --> 00:07:03.556 A:middle
Here is what an existing
TTY machine looks like.

00:07:04.386 --> 00:07:05.956 A:middle
As you can see, it's
fairly large

00:07:06.016 --> 00:07:07.966 A:middle
and probably difficult
to carry around.

00:07:08.476 --> 00:07:10.646 A:middle
But it's incredibly important
for someone who's deaf,

00:07:10.906 --> 00:07:13.906 A:middle
especially when you factor in
relay operators who translate

00:07:13.906 --> 00:07:17.146 A:middle
from TTY to voice, allowing
someone using this machine

00:07:17.146 --> 00:07:20.116 A:middle
to contact businesses,
services and family and friends

00:07:20.116 --> 00:07:20.936 A:middle
who may not be using one.

00:07:21.736 --> 00:07:23.476 A:middle
We thought it would be
great if the functionality

00:07:23.476 --> 00:07:25.216 A:middle
of this device was
available to everyone

00:07:25.476 --> 00:07:26.656 A:middle
without any additional hardware.

00:07:27.666 --> 00:07:31.386 A:middle
So new in iOS X anyone can
play software TTY phone calls

00:07:31.696 --> 00:07:33.236 A:middle
in a familiar interface
without having

00:07:33.236 --> 00:07:34.436 A:middle
to use any additional hardware.

00:07:35.256 --> 00:07:39.156 A:middle
These calls work with legacy
TTY technology and make it easy

00:07:39.156 --> 00:07:42.286 A:middle
to dial a non-TTY number through
your carrier's relay service.

00:07:42.956 --> 00:07:43.896 A:middle
Plus, it has built

00:07:43.896 --> 00:07:47.356 A:middle
in TTY-specific quick type
predictions so it fits

00:07:47.356 --> 00:07:49.206 A:middle
in with existing
TTY user culture.

00:07:49.756 --> 00:07:50.656 A:middle
And finally, learning.

00:07:51.626 --> 00:07:54.766 A:middle
Dyslexia is an incredibly common
learning disability affecting

00:07:54.766 --> 00:07:56.716 A:middle
the ability to read
and write of millions

00:07:56.716 --> 00:07:57.576 A:middle
of people around the world.

00:07:58.246 --> 00:08:00.276 A:middle
In iOS X we're excited
to bring a number


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:07:58.246 --> 00:08:00.276 A:middle
In iOS X we're excited
to bring a number

00:08:00.276 --> 00:08:02.476 A:middle
of enhancements designed to
help people with dyslexia.

00:08:03.496 --> 00:08:05.606 A:middle
We've implemented
improvements to Speak Selection

00:08:06.106 --> 00:08:08.656 A:middle
and Speak Screen to help people
better understand the text

00:08:08.656 --> 00:08:09.506 A:middle
that's already been entered.

00:08:09.906 --> 00:08:12.216 A:middle
And we've implemented new
audio feedback for typing

00:08:12.286 --> 00:08:13.936 A:middle
to help people immediately
catch mistakes.

00:08:14.006 --> 00:08:16.136 A:middle
And I'd love to show
that you now.

00:08:16.426 --> 00:08:19.716 A:middle
Okay, so I've turned on typing
feedback features already

00:08:19.716 --> 00:08:21.016 A:middle
in Accessibility
Speech Settings.

00:08:21.016 --> 00:08:22.366 A:middle
So I'll just fire up Notes.

00:08:22.656 --> 00:08:24.296 A:middle
And what I'm going to
do here is I'm going

00:08:24.296 --> 00:08:25.906 A:middle
to type the word
Welcome and I'm going

00:08:25.946 --> 00:08:27.496 A:middle
to pause after typing the O.

00:08:28.306 --> 00:08:29.896 A:middle
And I've turned on
Character Feedback

00:08:30.316 --> 00:08:33.306 A:middle
where iOS will read the last
character that I typed back

00:08:33.306 --> 00:08:35.236 A:middle
to me after a pause
so I can be sure

00:08:35.236 --> 00:08:38.476 A:middle
that I didn't enter a visually
similar character like an E.

00:08:41.426 --> 00:08:41.655 A:middle
&gt;&gt; E.

00:08:42.366 --> 00:08:45.216 A:middle
&gt;&gt; So, it may be difficult
to hear a little bit,

00:08:45.216 --> 00:08:47.666 A:middle
but iOS just read
back an E to me.

00:08:47.936 --> 00:08:49.186 A:middle
So that wasn't correct.

00:08:50.426 --> 00:08:50.986 A:middle
&gt;&gt; O.

00:08:50.986 --> 00:08:55.016 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Great. Now, I'm going
to keep typing, excuse me,

00:08:55.056 --> 00:08:58.006 A:middle
and iOS is going to read
back each word to me,

00:08:58.006 --> 00:08:59.566 A:middle
because I've turned
on Word Feedback.

00:08:59.566 --> 00:09:01.046 A:middle
So I can get immediate feedback


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:08:59.566 --> 00:09:01.046 A:middle
So I can get immediate feedback

00:09:01.046 --> 00:09:03.476 A:middle
as to whether the word I've
entered is the one I wanted.

00:09:04.716 --> 00:09:10.096 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Welcome to our session.

00:09:10.556 --> 00:09:12.316 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Okay. So that's
a quick example

00:09:12.316 --> 00:09:16.976 A:middle
of enhanced typing
feedback in iOS X.

00:09:19.406 --> 00:09:21.356 A:middle
So, hopefully I've whetted
your appetite as to the kinds

00:09:21.356 --> 00:09:23.096 A:middle
of accommodations
software can provide

00:09:23.416 --> 00:09:25.296 A:middle
to make sure the entire
experience is accessible

00:09:25.296 --> 00:09:25.766 A:middle
to everyone.

00:09:26.336 --> 00:09:27.516 A:middle
So if you're new
to accessibility,

00:09:27.516 --> 00:09:30.166 A:middle
you may be wondering about
how you can put similar

00:09:30.166 --> 00:09:31.476 A:middle
accommodations into your apps.

00:09:31.966 --> 00:09:34.006 A:middle
And if you've used the
accessibilities APIs before,

00:09:34.486 --> 00:09:36.316 A:middle
maybe it's time for a quick
refresher before we jump

00:09:36.316 --> 00:09:37.146 A:middle
onto some new API.

00:09:37.796 --> 00:09:40.246 A:middle
So, how do we use the
accessibility APIs

00:09:40.246 --> 00:09:41.536 A:middle
to make sure our
apps are accessible?

00:09:42.956 --> 00:09:45.376 A:middle
Well, the first step is to
audit our app for accessibility.

00:09:46.246 --> 00:09:48.296 A:middle
Traditionally, the best way
to do this was just to fire

00:09:48.296 --> 00:09:50.686 A:middle
up an assistive app like
VoiceOver or Switch Control

00:09:50.686 --> 00:09:51.476 A:middle
and see what happened.

00:09:52.326 --> 00:09:54.216 A:middle
You'll want to check that
all your interface items

00:09:54.216 --> 00:09:54.856 A:middle
are exposed.

00:09:56.026 --> 00:09:58.196 A:middle
That everything that is
exposed has a good label

00:09:58.196 --> 00:10:00.506 A:middle
so someone using
VoiceOver can identify it.


