00:13:38.556 --> 00:13:40.286 A:middle
So, what did we learn
about our app?

00:13:40.906 --> 00:13:42.296 A:middle
First, those route list cells.

00:13:42.556 --> 00:13:45.346 A:middle
The Favorite button has that
odd label that's derived

00:13:45.346 --> 00:13:46.576 A:middle
from the name of the
image we're using.

00:13:47.116 --> 00:13:49.556 A:middle
In addition, it isn't clear

00:13:49.556 --> 00:13:52.066 A:middle
that the table cell itself can
be activated to go somewhere.

00:13:52.546 --> 00:13:55.666 A:middle
Now, for the ratings graph,

00:13:55.666 --> 00:13:58.956 A:middle
those graph values were totally
inaccessible to VoiceOver.

00:13:59.506 --> 00:14:04.696 A:middle
And finally, in the route step
list the cells representing


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:13:59.506 --> 00:14:04.696 A:middle
And finally, in the route step
list the cells representing

00:14:04.696 --> 00:14:07.326 A:middle
waypoints that were hazards
are not differentiated

00:14:07.326 --> 00:14:08.426 A:middle
from the other steps
on the route.

00:14:09.526 --> 00:14:11.076 A:middle
So how can we fix
these problems?

00:14:12.976 --> 00:14:14.526 A:middle
Well, to understand how, we need

00:14:14.526 --> 00:14:17.136 A:middle
to understand how VoiceOver
is able to access information

00:14:17.136 --> 00:14:18.296 A:middle
from our interface and drive it.

00:14:19.046 --> 00:14:20.416 A:middle
VoiceOver interacts with our app

00:14:20.536 --> 00:14:22.076 A:middle
through the UIAccessibility
protocol.

00:14:23.016 --> 00:14:25.466 A:middle
So let's take, as an
example, that Favorite button

00:14:25.466 --> 00:14:28.846 A:middle
in the app we just saw.

00:14:28.846 --> 00:14:30.596 A:middle
Assistive apps like
VoiceOver need

00:14:30.596 --> 00:14:33.356 A:middle
to ask your app's user
interface items questions.

00:14:33.626 --> 00:14:36.156 A:middle
So for instance, when Voiceover
is on and someone touches

00:14:36.156 --> 00:14:38.666 A:middle
that button, VoiceOver
asks the button, "Hey,

00:14:38.666 --> 00:14:39.716 A:middle
what kind of thing are you?"

00:14:39.716 --> 00:14:41.906 A:middle
And the button says,
"Well, I'm a button."

00:14:43.006 --> 00:14:44.546 A:middle
VoiceOver then asks,
"Who are you?

00:14:44.546 --> 00:14:45.186 A:middle
What's your name?"

00:14:45.566 --> 00:14:49.006 A:middle
That button should respond
with something like "Favorite."

00:14:49.976 --> 00:14:52.536 A:middle
Finally VoiceOver asks,
"Where are you on screen?"

00:14:52.906 --> 00:14:55.036 A:middle
And the button replies with
"Its screen space frame."

00:14:55.746 --> 00:14:57.886 A:middle
This is the information
VoiceOver needs to announce,

00:14:58.156 --> 00:15:00.826 A:middle
"Favorite, Button" and draw
a cursor around the element.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:14:58.156 --> 00:15:00.826 A:middle
"Favorite, Button" and draw
a cursor around the element.

00:15:02.036 --> 00:15:04.326 A:middle
So these messages from
assistive technologies

00:15:04.326 --> 00:15:06.596 A:middle
to your app take the form
of method invocations.

00:15:06.996 --> 00:15:09.376 A:middle
The methods are all part of
the UIAccessibility protocol.

00:15:09.956 --> 00:15:10.866 A:middle
By implementing the methods

00:15:10.866 --> 00:15:12.846 A:middle
of this protocol you
make your custom view

00:15:12.846 --> 00:15:13.896 A:middle
hierarchies accessible.

00:15:14.376 --> 00:15:17.766 A:middle
So standard UI controls
have accessibility baked in.

00:15:18.166 --> 00:15:20.106 A:middle
But depending on how you
configure them, you may need

00:15:20.106 --> 00:15:21.836 A:middle
to set or override
certain properties.

00:15:22.256 --> 00:15:23.076 A:middle
So what properties?

00:15:23.346 --> 00:15:23.846 A:middle
Let's take a look.

00:15:24.866 --> 00:15:27.966 A:middle
Now, there are a lot of methods
on the UIAccessibility protocol

00:15:27.966 --> 00:15:29.916 A:middle
that you can use for
fine-grained control

00:15:30.176 --> 00:15:32.226 A:middle
over how your interface
items expose themselves

00:15:32.226 --> 00:15:32.916 A:middle
to accessibility.

00:15:33.326 --> 00:15:34.346 A:middle
But for most work you need

00:15:34.346 --> 00:15:35.906 A:middle
to only concern yourself
with a few.

00:15:36.566 --> 00:15:38.826 A:middle
Let's go through the basic
properties one by one.

00:15:39.166 --> 00:15:41.166 A:middle
First, there's
isAccessibilityElement.

00:15:42.296 --> 00:15:45.006 A:middle
This property determines if
an interface item is serviced

00:15:45.156 --> 00:15:46.456 A:middle
by an assistive technology
at all.

00:15:47.066 --> 00:15:49.126 A:middle
So for instance, if you have
an image view that's background

00:15:49.126 --> 00:15:51.746 A:middle
decoration, you can
leave this as False.

00:15:52.316 --> 00:15:54.916 A:middle
However, if it represents a
photo that someone uploaded

00:15:54.916 --> 00:15:57.356 A:middle
to your service, you'll
want to set this to True

00:15:57.356 --> 00:15:59.446 A:middle
so someone using VoiceOver
can discover the image,

00:15:59.686 --> 00:16:01.486 A:middle
focus on it and learn about it.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:15:59.686 --> 00:16:01.486 A:middle
focus on it and learn about it.

00:16:03.166 --> 00:16:06.226 A:middle
So now your interface element
is surfaced by VoiceOver.

00:16:06.226 --> 00:16:08.856 A:middle
You'll want to give it a name
so that users can identify it.

00:16:09.016 --> 00:16:10.696 A:middle
That's what the accessibility
label is for.

00:16:11.466 --> 00:16:13.616 A:middle
The label is a concise
identifier of the element.

00:16:13.966 --> 00:16:16.326 A:middle
For instance Send
Message or New Alarm.

00:16:16.966 --> 00:16:21.496 A:middle
So how does someone know that
they can activate your element?

00:16:22.246 --> 00:16:25.306 A:middle
New Alarm doesn't convey
that the item is a button

00:16:25.306 --> 00:16:27.326 A:middle
in the same way that its
visual styling might.

00:16:27.976 --> 00:16:29.556 A:middle
That's where the
accessibility traits come in.

00:16:30.396 --> 00:16:31.776 A:middle
Accessibility traits declare

00:16:31.776 --> 00:16:34.386 A:middle
to the assistive technology
what your element is

00:16:34.386 --> 00:16:35.516 A:middle
and how to interact with it.

00:16:35.906 --> 00:16:37.656 A:middle
So for instance, a button
should have the trait

00:16:37.656 --> 00:16:39.016 A:middle
UIAccessibilityTraitButton.

00:16:40.016 --> 00:16:41.336 A:middle
An adjustable control

00:16:41.336 --> 00:16:43.166 A:middle
like a slider would
have the trait

00:16:43.166 --> 00:16:44.686 A:middle
UIAccessibilityTraitAdjustable.

00:16:45.346 --> 00:16:46.506 A:middle
The traits are a bit masked,

00:16:46.506 --> 00:16:47.946 A:middle
so an element could
have more than one.

00:16:48.466 --> 00:16:50.276 A:middle
For instance, a selected
button should have both

00:16:50.566 --> 00:16:54.156 A:middle
UIAccessibilityTraitButton and
UIAccessibiltyTraitSelected.

00:16:54.566 --> 00:16:57.216 A:middle
The Button trait is what
makes VoiceOver speak "Button"

00:16:57.636 --> 00:16:59.336 A:middle
so someone knows they can
activate your element.

00:16:59.776 --> 00:17:03.386 A:middle
Next there's the
accessibility frame.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:16:59.776 --> 00:17:03.386 A:middle
Next there's the
accessibility frame.

00:17:04.056 --> 00:17:06.366 A:middle
This determines where
your element is onscreen

00:17:06.366 --> 00:17:07.866 A:middle
and is used both for hit testing

00:17:07.906 --> 00:17:09.756 A:middle
and for drawing a cursor
around the element.

00:17:10.445 --> 00:17:13.886 A:middle
Now, for UI views you usually do
not have to set this explicitly

00:17:14.106 --> 00:17:17.046 A:middle
because it's computed for you
based on where the view is

00:17:17.046 --> 00:17:17.806 A:middle
in the view hierarchy.

00:17:18.925 --> 00:17:20.455 A:middle
But you can modify it if needed.

00:17:20.455 --> 00:17:22.695 A:middle
Just remember that it is
in screen coordinates.

00:17:23.205 --> 00:17:26.496 A:middle
And finally, there's
the accessibility value.

00:17:27.316 --> 00:17:29.036 A:middle
This is useful for
elements that have some sort

00:17:29.036 --> 00:17:30.986 A:middle
of conceptual value
associated with them.

00:17:31.576 --> 00:17:34.366 A:middle
So for instance, a slider
returns its current value

00:17:34.366 --> 00:17:35.946 A:middle
in percent through the
accessibility value.

00:17:36.606 --> 00:17:38.486 A:middle
An on-off switch
returns on or off.

00:17:38.666 --> 00:17:40.336 A:middle
And if you had some
sort of custom control

00:17:40.336 --> 00:17:41.966 A:middle
that controlled the
magnification level

00:17:41.966 --> 00:17:45.886 A:middle
of an instrument, you'd want to
convey that magnification level

00:17:45.886 --> 00:17:47.016 A:middle
through the accessibility value.

00:17:47.596 --> 00:17:52.016 A:middle
Okay, so what do you do
if you do custom drawing

00:17:52.616 --> 00:17:55.406 A:middle
where each logical piece of your
interface doesn't map directly

00:17:55.406 --> 00:17:56.086 A:middle
to a UI view?

00:17:57.256 --> 00:17:59.776 A:middle
When you need to do that,
use UIAccessibilityElement.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:18:00.496 --> 00:18:04.086 A:middle
UIAccessibilityElement objects
represent logical accessible

00:18:04.086 --> 00:18:04.946 A:middle
regions onscreen.

00:18:05.276 --> 00:18:08.006 A:middle
And they interact with the
UIAccessibility protocol just

00:18:08.006 --> 00:18:09.106 A:middle
like your views do.

00:18:09.546 --> 00:18:12.396 A:middle
You can use them, for instance,
to expose each individual piece

00:18:12.396 --> 00:18:14.716 A:middle
of a control that's built
as a single UI view.

00:18:15.496 --> 00:18:19.856 A:middle
So to do so, make the element
whose pieces you want to expose

00:18:19.856 --> 00:18:21.246 A:middle
into an accessibility container

00:18:21.726 --> 00:18:24.736 A:middle
by setting its accessibility
elements property to an array

00:18:24.736 --> 00:18:26.496 A:middle
of UIAccessibilityElement
objects

00:18:26.556 --> 00:18:29.226 A:middle
that represent each
individual piece of the control.

00:18:30.976 --> 00:18:34.386 A:middle
So, UIAccessibilityElement
is a natural choice to expose

00:18:34.386 --> 00:18:37.386 A:middle
that graph we saw earlier where
I was doing some custom layers

00:18:37.766 --> 00:18:39.786 A:middle
to present the graph bars.

00:18:40.306 --> 00:18:42.316 A:middle
But if you're a very astute
listener you may have noticed a

00:18:42.316 --> 00:18:42.916 A:middle
slight snag.

00:18:45.456 --> 00:18:47.916 A:middle
UIAccessibilityElement
objects aren't views,

00:18:48.006 --> 00:18:49.986 A:middle
so we need to set their
accessibility frame manually.

00:18:50.516 --> 00:18:53.876 A:middle
However, those graph bars
were inside of a scroll view,

00:18:54.136 --> 00:18:56.316 A:middle
so their frames and
screen coordinates change.

00:18:57.136 --> 00:18:59.386 A:middle
Now, to rectify this
we could subclass,

00:18:59.386 --> 00:19:01.746 A:middle
or we could set accessibility
frame after each scroll.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:18:59.386 --> 00:19:01.746 A:middle
or we could set accessibility
frame after each scroll.

00:19:02.326 --> 00:19:05.806 A:middle
Or, in iOS X we can
set accessibility frame

00:19:05.806 --> 00:19:06.806 A:middle
in container space.

00:19:07.396 --> 00:19:10.676 A:middle
When you set this property to
a container-relative frame,

00:19:11.576 --> 00:19:14.816 A:middle
UIAccessibilityElement will
automatically follow its

00:19:14.816 --> 00:19:16.236 A:middle
container's position onscreen.

00:19:16.806 --> 00:19:20.446 A:middle
So those are the
most basic methods

